Analysis of Tottenham’s 2023-2024 Season Performance in the Premier League So Far¶

Stand: 15/01/2024

Anh Viet Ngo - January 2024

Data Source: Football Data from Transfermarkt

Code source: Github - Football Analysis

1. Introduction¶

In this analysis, I will focus on analyzing Tottenham Hotspur's performance so far in the 2023-2024 Premier League season. At the time I posted this analysis, the 21th round just ended for Tottenham.

The Data consists of 9 CSV files that record data about football players and clubs including the data from matches that occur with them. I will use these files to extract important information about the team's performance. With the code I provide in Python, you can choose any clubs and seasons since the 2012-2023 season due to the dates available among files.

Throughout this analysis you will be able to understand the following:

Clubs' main information: Link on Transfermarkt, Name, Stadium, Coach, Total Market Value...

Players's information of that season (2023-2024)

Goals and assists analysis

Games results and position in the table

Cards analysis and how it affects the game's result

Analysis of players with the most contributions in the season

Use the code I provide in Python for analysis of any clubs you are interested in in a season between 2012 and now. I also a Power BI report for this analysis in the input (.pdf and .pbix file).

2. Data Wrangling¶

In this part, we will focus on cleaning the data by turning raw data into usable form for further analysis. This could be creating more columns in certain tables to gain more insights about the data based on existing columns like retrieving month or year from date column, Calculate total goals or getting only the data of the club and season we want to analyze, or adjusting the existing data types to a more reasonable one.

But first things first, we should import all necessary libraries and CSV files:

In [4]:
#Get all domestic games in that season
games['date'] = pd.to_datetime(games['date'])
games = games[((games['home_club_id'] == club_id) | (games['away_club_id'] == club_id)) & (games['season'] == season)]
games_id = games[games['competition_id'] == league_id].sort_values(by='round')['game_id'].tolist()
domestic_game = games[games['competition_id'] == league_id].sort_values(by='date')

#Create an extra column which calculates the number of goals in a match
club_games = club_games[((club_games['club_id'] == club_id)) & (club_games['game_id'].isin(games_id))]
club_games['total_goals'] = club_games['own_goals'] + club_games['opponent_goals']
club_games['clean_sheets'] = club_games.apply(
    lambda row: 1 if (row['opponent_id'] == 148 and row['own_goals'] == 0) | (row['club_id'] == 148 and row['opponent_goals'] == 0) else 0,
    axis=1
)

game_events = game_events[(game_events['club_id'] == club_id ) & (game_events['game_id'].isin(games_id))]
game_lineups = game_lineups[(game_lineups['club_id'] == club_id ) & (game_lineups['game_id'].isin(games_id))]

Then we want to retrieve the following players of the season with the appearances table by getting all the names of players who have made at least one appearance in the season and filter it through the players table. Therefore players who haven't made any appearances for the club in the season will not appear in the table. We could fix this by filtering directly with the player's table by using the 'current_club_id' column, but it will only work for the current season and players who left the club in the current season will also not appear in the table, so, for scalability, I would rather use the first option because by filtering out players who haven't played any games for the club in the season won't affect our analysis.

In [5]:
#Get all players in the season
appearances = appearances[appearances['player_club_id'] == club_id]
appearances = appearances[(appearances['game_id'].isin(games_id)) & (appearances['player_club_id'] == club_id)]
get_all_players = set(appearances['player_id'].to_list())

#Make an categorical order for the positions
order = ['Goalkeeper', 'Defender', 'Midfield', 'Attack']
players['position'] = pd.Categorical(players['position'], categories=order, ordered=True)
players['date_of_birth'] = pd.to_datetime(players['date_of_birth'])
players['is_foreigner'] = np.where(players['country_of_citizenship'] != club_country, 1, 0)
players['age'] = season - players['date_of_birth'].dt.year

player_values['date'] = pd.to_datetime(player_values['date'])
player_values['month_year'] = player_values['date'].apply(lambda x: f"08 {x.year}" if x >= pd.Timestamp(x.year, 7, 1) else f"08 {x.year-1}")
player_values['season'] = player_values['date'].apply(lambda x: f"{x.year}-{x.year+1}" if x >= pd.Timestamp(x.year, 7, 1) else f"{x.year-1}-{x.year}")
player_values = player_values.loc[player_values.groupby(['player_id','season'])['date'].idxmin()] #Get value only at start of season

players_current_season = players[players['player_id'].isin(get_all_players)]
players_current_season['season_start'] = f'08 {season}'

#Get the value of the following season
players_current_season = players_current_season.merge(player_values[['player_id', 'market_value_in_eur', 'month_year']], 
                left_on=['season_start', 'player_id'], right_on=['month_year', 'player_id'])
attribute = ['name', 'country_of_citizenship', 'date_of_birth', 'sub_position', 'foot', 'height_in_cm', 'market_value_in_eur_y'] #Attribute for the display the players

4. Goals and Assists's Analysis¶

Now we will take a deeper look into the goal contribution by analyzing some important aspects that affect the team performance like the number of goals in a single match, goal distribution, top scorer, and top assisters:

In [8]:
#Goals per Player
goal_assist = appearances.groupby('player_name')[['goals', 'assists']].sum()
goal = goal_assist[goal_assist['goals'] > 0].sort_values(by='goals', ascending = False).reset_index()
sns.barplot(data=goal, y='player_name', x='goals')
plt.title('Goal per Player')
plt.xlabel('Number of goals')
plt.ylabel('Player')
plt.show()

#Assists per Player
assist = goal_assist[goal_assist['assists'] > 0].sort_values(by='assists', ascending = False).reset_index()
sns.barplot(data=assist, y='player_name', x='assists')
plt.title('Assist per Player')
plt.xlabel('Number of assists')
plt.ylabel('Player')
plt.show()

The contribution from goals and assists comes mostly from our most used XI with Heung-min Son as the top scorer (12 Goals) and Pedro Porro (8 Assists) as the top assister.

One more thing to notice that I mentioned before is the absence of James Maddison in the XI, although he has a substantial goal contribution for the club with already 3 Goals and 6 Assists. With his return in the squad the team's performance could be improved significantly.

Because there can sometimes be more than 1 players who have the most goal contribution, therefore players with the most goal contribution:

Now we want to see goal distribution in a match, which is divided into 10 buckets of 10 minutes:

The team tends to score goals in the last 10 minutes of the game and more goals in the second half than in the first half. It could also mean that the team is better at adapting to the game as it progresses and making strategic changes to their gameplay. Moreover, they are also likely to score in the first 20 minutes of the game.

In [11]:
goal_col = club_games['own_goals']
bins = [0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5, 5.5]
bin_labels = ['0.5', '1.5', '2.5', '3.5', '4.5', '5.5']

# Calculate percentage distribution of total goals
lower = [np.sum(goal_col < bin) / len(goal_col) * 100 for bin in bins]
higher = [np.sum(goal_col > bin) / len(goal_col) * 100 for bin in bins]

fig, plot_percentage = plt.subplots()
plot_percentage.barh(bin_labels, lower, label='Lower')
plot_percentage.barh(bin_labels, higher, left=lower, label='Higher')

plot_percentage.set_xlabel('Percentage')
plot_percentage.set_ylabel('Goal Interval')
plot_percentage.set_title('Percentage distribution of goals')
plot_percentage.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper left')

#Conceded Goals
conceed_col = club_games['opponent_goals']
lower = [np.sum(conceed_col < bin) / len(goal_col) * 100 for bin in bins]
higher = [np.sum(conceed_col > bin) / len(goal_col) * 100 for bin in bins]

figu, plot_percentages = plt.subplots()
plot_percentages.barh(bin_labels, lower, label='Lower')
plot_percentages.barh(bin_labels, higher, left=lower, label='Higher')

plot_percentages.set_xlabel('Percentage')
plot_percentages.set_ylabel('Goal Interval')
plot_percentages.set_title('Percentage distribution of conceded goals')
plot_percentages.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper left')

plt.show()

The team happens to always score at least 1 goal in a match and the probability of having more than 2 goals in a match is nearly 80% through the bar chart above we can see that Tottenham normally scores 2 goals in a game. This indicates that Tottenham is an offensive team that has a consistent goal rate.

On the other hand, the percentage they conceded at least a goal in a match is also pretty high with nearly 80% chance. This shows that we still need to improve our defense for better results and not drop points despite being able to score goals.

'''points per match/ standing'''
results = {'win': 0, 'draw': 0, 'lose': 0}

# Check for wins, draws, and losses
for index, row in domestic_game.iterrows():
    if row['home_club_id'] == club_id:
        if row['home_club_goals'] > row['away_club_goals']:
            results['win'] += 1
        elif row['home_club_goals'] == row['away_club_goals']:
            results['draw'] += 1
        else:
            results['lose'] += 1
    elif row['away_club_id'] == club_id:
        if row['away_club_goals'] > row['home_club_goals']:
            results['win'] += 1
        elif row['away_club_goals'] == row['home_club_goals']:
            results['draw'] += 1
        else:
            results['lose'] += 1
print(f"Results in the season: {results}")

'''Home, Away results'''
home = {'win': 0, 'draw': 0, 'lose': 0}
for index, row in domestic_game.iterrows():
    if row['home_club_id'] == club_id:
        if row['home_club_goals'] > row['away_club_goals']:
            home['win'] += 1
        elif row['home_club_goals'] == row['away_club_goals']:
            home['draw'] += 1
        else:
            home['lose'] += 1
print(f"\nResults when playing at home: {home}")

away = {'win': 0, 'draw': 0, 'lose': 0}
for index, row in domestic_game.iterrows():
    if row['away_club_id'] == club_id:
        if row['away_club_goals'] > row['home_club_goals']:
            away['win'] += 1
        elif row['away_club_goals'] == row['home_club_goals']:
            away['draw'] += 1
        else:
            away['lose'] += 1
print(f"\nResults when playing away from home: {away}")

#Points per game
points_per_game = (results['win'] * 3 + results['draw']) / (results['win'] + results['draw'] + results['lose'])
print(f"\nAfter {results['win'] + results['draw'] + results['lose']} matches the team gets an average of {round(points_per_game, 2)} points per game")

#Clean sheets
clean_sheets = club_games['clean_sheets'].sum()
print(f'\nThe club has {clean_sheets} matches where they conceeded no goal ({round(clean_sheets/len(club_games) * 100, 2)}%)')

    players_current = players_current.merge(player_value[['player_id', 'market_value_in_eur', 'month_year']], 
                    left_on=['season_start', 'player_id'], right_on=['month_year', 'player_id'])
    players_current.drop_duplicates(subset=['player_id'], inplace=True)
    
    market_value.append(players_current['market_value_in_eur_y'].sum())

team_name = [name.replace(" Football Club", "") for name in team_name] #Shorten the name but only applied for English club

#pair sort the team and their values
team_and_market_value = list(zip(team_name, market_value))
team_and_market_value.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])
team_name, market_value = zip(*team_and_market_value)

ax = plt.gca()
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(format_func))

The current position corresponds to the market value compared with other teams in the league. But there was a period when Tottenham remained in the Top 2 for a long time before falling out of the top 4 in recent rounds. 7. Conclusion¶

Key findings:

Tottenham Hotspur is an offensive team that has a high scoring rate, especially in the second half and the last 10 minutes of the game.

The team relies heavily on the goal contribution of Heung-min Son, who is the top scorer and the captain of the team.

The team also has a high rate of foreign players, who perform better than the domestic players.

However, the team has a weak defense, as they concede at least one goal in most of their matches. The team struggles to keep clean sheets and earn points, especially away from home.

The team’s total market value is also correlated with their position in the table

The team’s performance could be improved by the return of James Maddison, who is a key player in the midfield.

A high number of yellow cards per match (2.8).

Yves Bissouma is the only player who appears in top players with both red and yellow cards.

Are still able to manage to maintain good results after receiving a red card.

Tottenham has the tendency to get cards at the end of each half.

Recommendations for improvements:

Strengthen the defense by signing or developing more reliable defenders, who can prevent the opponents from scoring and creating chances.

Improve the team’s tactical flexibility and adaptability, by using different formations and strategies depending on the opponent and the situation of the game. This could help the team to play flexibly with the remaining players when key players become injured.

Increase the involvement and creativity of other players, besides Heung-min Son, who can provide more goals and assists for the team.

Manage the fitness and morale of the players, by rotating the squad and giving them enough rest and motivation.

Try to earn as many points as possible when playing at home under huge support from home fans.

Reduce the number of cards per match, by avoiding unnecessary fouls and respecting the referee’s decisions.

Improve the discipline and temperament of Yves Bissouma.
